<td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/red_05.gif" class="headerbg"><font class="h1font"><font color="#FFFFFF"><table cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0 border=0 width=100%><TR><td><font class="h1font">Articles</td><form method='post' action=''><input type="hidden" name="PHPSESSID" value="2bd8be4bbdbdbe86d1c366aea8e77e69" /><td align='right' valign='bottom'><select name='select' onChange='go(this)'><option selected>More DeckTech Articles</option><option value='#'> </option><option value='/starwarsccg/articles/index.php3'>Star Wars: CCG</option><option value='/vs/articles/index.php'>Marvel VS</option><option value='/heroclix/articles/articles.php'>HeroClix</option><option value='/lotr/articles/articles.php'>Lord of the Rings</option><option value='/magination/articles/articles.php'>Magi-Nation Duel</option><option value='/swtcg/articles/articles.php'>Ophidian 2350</option><option value='/magic/treports/treports.php'>The Wastelands</option></select></td></form></tr></table></font></B></td><td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/red_06.gif"></td></tr>
	<tr><td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/whi_07.gif"></td>
		<td bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/lotr/gfx/mom/whi_08.gif"><font class="bfont"><font class="h1font"> Hobbits on Wallstreet<br></font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Overall Rating:</b> </font><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><font size='1'>(4.74)</font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Author:</b> <A HREF='http://www.decktech.net/lotr/main/mpage.php?member=6495'>Devon "Devonator" Clark</A></font><font class="afont"> <a href='http://www.decktech.net/lotr/main/mpage.php?member=6495&sub=1'> (Subscribe to this member)</a><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Date Submitted:</b> February 8, 2002</font><p align='justify'><font class="bfont"> You&#39;ve recently begun to invest in the Middle-Earth exchange.  Your portfolio is turning out excellent!  The CEOs of Mordor and Isengard are secretly negotiating a merger and as a result speculation has caused their stocks to rise . . . for the short term, anyway.  In other markets, Moria Mines is under new management but pressure from a remaining stockholder has caused shares of Moria to split.  Of course, not every stock in your portfolio has such a promising future: The threat of a hostile takeover by Servants of the Secret Fire has caused shares of Balrog to plummet.  Still, what few losses you have are more than counterbalanced by your investment in the First Bank of Shirefolk.  True, the bank is small.  Not many investors know that it exists at all, but those that do swear by it.  Investing in Hobbit futures is very lucrative, they tell you.  And though it may seem funny when the Board of Directors walks into a stockholders&#39; meeting with their furry bare feet, you know that this company is going to take the Middle-Earth Exchange by storm.  They are masters of a new economy--a token economy.  And you know that they are the one stock to rule them all!<br />
<br />
Mastering the Lord of the Rings Trading Card Game is a difficult process--a task fraught with obstacles at every stop along the adventure path.  In your quest to master the game, you must have many tools at your disposal in order to achieve true success.  You must have a competitive deck, an awareness of available cards and combinations, knowledge of game mechanics, and much more.  All in all, a very daunting task!  Well, in an attempt to guide you to said mastery of the game, this article will focus on the economics of game play.  Your first step along the Lord of the Rings path . . . follow in the footsteps of the First Bank of Shirefolk.  Master the economics of LotR.  <br />
<br />
At first glance, LotR economics might seem like an unsubstantial topic.  You might expect me to speak marginally about twilight pool management but little else.  Well, this is not the case.  The twilight pool is only half of the Middle-Earth economic spectrum.  There is evidence of a market economy everywhere along the adventure path, and for that reason, this article will speak at great length about many of these economic parallels.  That is why I encourage you to think like an economist and follow three simple, yet extremely important, rules for investment . . . and consequently, LotR success!<br />
<br />
1.	Buy Low, Sell High.<br />
2.	Have clearly defined, attainable goals.<br />
3.	Balance short-term and long-term goals.<br />
<br />
If you follow these three fundamental rules during preparation and play (or as I like to say, from deck design to site 9), you will find that you have placed yourself in the best possible situation to succeed.  So, to aid you in this endeavor, to marshal you closer to that perfect understanding of LotR economics, I will elaborate on all of the above rules.  But first, allow me to expand on my assumptions for the Middle-Earth economy so that we can share a common understanding of our market before we begin to invest . . . <br />
<br />
Economic Overview:<br />
<br />
As a fellow LotR player, you will probably accept my assumption that there are two economies in Middle-Earth--the Shadow and the Free People.  Each of these economies has their own separate dynamic and culture.  For that reason, they also have separate forms of legal tender, and there is a constant barter system between the two.  Immediately, you will identify one of the two currencies--the Shadow economy is indeed driven by Twilight--however the Free People&#39;s coin is a more elusive thing.  Contrary to popular belief, it is NOT twilight . . . nor is it the dollar, euro, or yen.  No, the currency of Free Middle-Earth is the wound.  Now, some of you might argue that both the fellowship and the shadow purchase their assets with twilight, and in a sense, this is true; but if you argue this point than you argue that the Free People is blessed with an endless line of credit and that the Shadow is a creditor constantly trying to foreclose.  Well, call me idealistic, but I prefer not to think of my fellowship as the Bundies of Middle-Earth, and in truth I would prefer that my metaphor be a more economically sound system than that.  Instead, I suggest that you think of LotR economics in this way: The Free People&#39;s chief export is twilight and the Shadow&#39;s chief export is the wound.  In the Free People&#39;s attempt to acquire better real estate, there is a constant exchange between the two societies.  The Free People provides the Shadow with Twilight, and the Shadow repays the Free People in wounds . . . and in this paradigm, wounds are the governing currency of Middle-Earth.  Every time you add Twilight to the pool, you incur a risk that your companions will take damage.  Every time you play a possession, condition, or companion, you have essentially affected a trade.  You give the Shadow twilight, and they in turn play additional minions adding additional sources of damage.  Therefore, the cost of an Aragorn at Site 4 is anywhere between 0 and 5 wounds.  The twilight cost is simply a portion of the rate of exchange.  In other words, you pay for your fellowship cards in blood.<br />
<br />
BUY LOW, SELL HIGH<br />
<br />
As I have proposed, there are two accepted currencies in Middle-Earth--Twilight and Wounds.  In order to truly master LotR economics, you must understand (either inherently or consciously) the interaction between these two currencies.  True, you may pay the Shadow an amount of Twilight equal to the cost of a Free People card, but the true cost of the card is in the number of wounds that your fellowship will receive as a result of the added Twilight.  As I have already stated, whenever you play a companion, possession, or condition, you incur a certain degree of risk that your fellowship will take wounds proportional to the amount of twilight added.  Those wounds are the true cost.  However, let me reiterate that this is a constant bartering system, and thus an imperfect science.  The value of a wound changes from site to site and from opponent to opponent.  In fact, as the Free People player, you have some measure of control over the value of a wound, and it is for this reason that, as the Free People player, your goal is to cut costs wherever possible.  The best things in life are free, but at the very least you want to buy as low as possible.  From deck design to site 9, you should make it your goal to minimize the number of wounds that your fellowship incurs.  Meanwhile, as the Shadow player, your goal is exactly the opposite.  You should make it your goal to inflict as many wounds as possible for the twilight given to you.  You should strive to ensure that there is never a free lunch . . . or at the very least never a free move.  Every decision that you make, whether it be related to deck design or game play, should be based upon those criteria--the number of wounds that your fellowship will receive or the number of wounds that your Shadow will deliver.  In this sense, if you can Buy Low and Sell High, you will win the vast majority of your games.<br />
<br />
As I said, it is extremely important that you understand the interaction between Twilight and Wounds.  As such, the most important measure of whether you are, in fact buying low and selling high (and perhaps the best instrument in assessing overall deck efficiency) is the Twilight-Wound rate of exchange.  Just as in the money markets of the world, there is a fluid rate of exchange between Middle-Earth currencies.  A typical rate of exchange is approximately 3 or 4 twilight per 1 wound; however there are many variables that factor into the rate of exchange.  Where are you on the adventure path?  Roaming minions have higher costs and therefore make wounds more expensive at early sites.  What Shadow culture is your opponent playing?  Uruk-hai do more damage than other minions and are therefore subject to lower (but more volatile) rates of exchange than Moria orcs.  What cards has your opponent been playing?  If your opponent hasn&#39;t been playing fellowship cards, statistically that player must be accumulating them in his hand, thereby increasing the Twilight-Wound rate of exchange with a lack of minions.  What cards do you have in your hand?  Many events increase the probability that your companions will win their skirmishes or reduce the effects of those skirmishes, thus increasing the rate of exchange.  As you can see, many factors affect the Twilight-Wound rate of exchange; therefore as a metric, it is very difficult to measure.  Still, you should try to maintain a constant estimate of the ratio so that you can plan your moves and strategy accordingly.  As the fellowship, strive to make the Twilight-Wound rate of exchange as high as possible.  3-4 twilight per wound is an average ratio.  2 or less is extremely bad (Site 5 alone would guarantee 4 wounds).  Ideally, the fellowship would like an exchange of 5+ twilight per wound.  If your fellowship is enjoying that kind of exchange rate, you are indeed buying low and should have little trouble racing to site 9, accumulating only 1 wound from sanctuary to sanctuary.  Of course, the opposite is true for the shadow.<br />
<br />
During deck design, to make the most efficient use of every card in your deck, choose Free People cards that maximize the Twilight-Wound rate of exchange and Shadow cards that minimize it.  For the Free People, cards such as Armor, No Stranger To The Shadows, and Power According to His Stature are ideal because each directly influences the rate of exchange.  Armor reduces the number of wounds received, NSttS reduces twilight, thus watering down the potential damage pool.  And PATHS eliminates sources of damage completely at almost no cost.  For this reason, it is one of the best cards in the game.  <br />
<br />
Conversely, as the Shadow, you want cards that do the most damage for their cost (overwhelming companions is equivalent to dealing that character the entirety of his remaining vitality).  Assuming that he does not overwhelm and is not roaming, the Cave Troll enjoys a 2.5 Twilight-Wound ratio, thus making him a better than average card; however, you can use the Cave Troll more effectively.  Play him underground and your ratio becomes 1.75.  Equip him with a hammer to lower that ratio to 1.33.  Finally, begin by playing his Keyward (presumably adding a wound) for a 1.29 ratio.  If you will remember that a 2 to 1 ratio is an excellent exchange, you can see how the Twilight-Wound rate of exchange provides an empirical measure of the Cave Troll&#39;s devastating capability.  Of course, I am not advocating that you play only minions.  Cards that reduce the Twilight-Wound rate of exchange such as Strength of Mordor, Lurtz&#39;s Battle Cry, They Are Coming, etc. are also excellent choices for you Shadow deck.  Strength of Mordor adds twilight to the pool; the Battle Cry adds a wound at almost no cost; and They Are Coming  (if used in conjunction with the right goblins) can add both wounds and twilight to the pool while also discarding cards for greater throughput.  For this reason, TAC is one of the best Shadow cards in the game.<br />
<br />
Yet, so far, I have only discussed the Twilight-Wound rate of exchange as it pertains to deck design, but this subject has a broader scope than that.  During game play, you should make an effort to either raise or lower the Twilight-Wound rate of exchange where possible.  Think of it as simply balancing your checkbook.  In this sense, you can use it as a tool during game play to measure your options against one and other and aid you in making the wisest decisions--both long-term and short-term.  Allow me to illustrate quickly my point.  Let&#39;s return to our most feared fiend--the Cave Troll.  Assume that you have Legolas Greenleaf, Sam Son of Hamfast, and Aragorn King In Exile accompanying Frodo on the path.  Aragorn is equipped with his bow, and both he and Legolas are swapping war stories (i.e., Legolas has the Tale of Gil-Galad and Aragorn has the Saga of Elendil).  Now, Site 5 is an extremely dangerous site (generally, site 5 enjoys a 2.5 Twilight-Wound rate of exchange) especially when playing against Moria, so you don&#39;t want to add any cards to your fellowship for fear of the added minions that the extra twilight will afford your opponent.  Instead, you simply move along giving your opponent 10 twilight.  In turn, he drops the Troll&#39;s Keyward and the Cave Troll with his hammer for 9 twilight.  You are looking at a possibility of 7 wounds (10 if you consider the Cave Trolls ability to overwhelm Aragorn and Legolas) inflicted upon your fellowship.  The Cave Troll alone accounts for 6 of those wounds.  However, if you balance your checkbook, you can see that there is a more ideal situation in which you will walk away with fewer wounds.  You can exert your archers 4 times to kill the troll, and then only have to worry about the Keyward, which you can then assign however you choose.  OR you can exhaust both of your archers and kill the Troll and the Keyward.  Obviously, that is not the solution as you would still amass the 7 wounds..  The best solution is to exert your archers 4 times to kill the troll, and then assign the Keyward to Aragorn who will take a wound.  You&#39;ve reduced the risk of 7 wounds to 5 wounds (Always remember, the exertion-wound rate of exchange is 1 to 1), and raised the Twilight-Wound rate of exchange from 1.47 to 2.0.  Now, imagine what might have happened had you added any extra twilight to the pool.  Equipped with awareness of the Twilight-Wound rate of exchange and by balancing your checkbook, you managed to maximize the rate of exchange and therefore increase your ability to reach site 9 alive.  <br />
<br />
Of course, what I&#39;m saying here is not revolutionary.  In fact, I am doing nothing more than restating a common sense observation.  Minimize the number of wounds that your Fellowship takes and maximize the number of wounds that your minions deal.  That&#39;s obvious.  But there is more.  The underlying principle which I am trying to make you understand is that there is a direct relationship between twilight and wounds, and if you understand how to use this Twilight-Wound rate of exchange as a benchmark for your deck&#39;s success, you will be one step closer to mastering the economy, and you will put yourself in a better position to win games.  It&#39;s as simple as that!<br />
<br />
HAVE CLEARLY DEFINED AND ATTAINABLE GOALS<br />
<br />
In one form or another, all competitors have a common goal-to achieve victory.  We all want to win.  However this goal is ambiguous.  It is little more than a wish-not a goal at all.  Of course we all want to win!  Unfortunately, not everybody is going to win.  It is the person who has envisioned his win before his game--the player that knows how he will achieve victory during a game--that will succeed in attaining that victory.  In all walks of LotR, clearly defined attainable goals determine your ability to overcome obstacles and steal that victory.  How do you want to win?  Will you race to site 9?  Will you overwhelm the ring-bearer?  Or will you have an equal opportunity for both?  If you intend to overwhelm, are you relying on a devastating 4 culture combo?  If so, your goal may not be attainable.  Or perhaps you intend to kill three of the fellowship&#39;s characters.  Well, your goal is not clearly defined.  I must impress upon you that this is not an either-or situation.  There is no middle ground.  You must have both or your deck will flounder.  It will become a paragon of mediocrity (and if you have neither, it might not even achieve that).  From the onset, in every aspect of the game, from deck design to site 9, you must have clear and attainable goals to achieve victory.  You must envision how your deck will win and you must be prepared to carry out that vision.  You&#39;ve probably heard sports figures the world over say &quot;See it before you do it&quot;.  Well, that adage is not sports specific.  It applies to everything in life, and that includes collectible card games.  You must know what your deck is capable of doing and you must know how to do what your deck is capable of.  Begin the deck building process with a vision of success in your mind.  If that vision is realistic, and if you hold true to that vision, you will make it reality.<br />
<br />
A large portion of creating clearly defined, attainable goals is having an awareness of the market and your assets.  The market, for our purposes here, is the type and level of resistance you will meet during play, whether that resistance is an opponent, a deck, or a specific card during play.  By knowing what you will face, you can create a goal to overcome the bear markets and defeat your opposition, and you can use that goal to build a successful deck.  If you consistently face Moria, you probably want a fellowship that can weather the swarms.  This becomes your goal.  You would probably build a fellowship with many companions to achieve this goal.  Having that clearly defined attainable goal has led you to build a competitive deck for your meta.  During a game, if your fellowship does not support many companions, you might hold onto a Valiant Man of the West for many sites knowing that you are going to get swarmed at site 5 or 8.  Your goal is to survive multiple minions at those sites and that goal has led you to make a decision that increases your chances for victory.  Simply put, clearly defined and attainable goals increase your chances for success.  <br />
<br />
To illustrate the importance of knowing the market and your assets, I would like to further elaborate on the Valiant Man of the West example.  Holding onto that Valiant Man of the West demonstrates an understanding of the market on many levels.  First, the deck designer has to know that Moria swarms would be a problem for his fellowship to include the Valiant Man of the West.  Then, the player would have to know that the Valiant Man of the West is an important card against a swarm deck to hold on to it.  At both the deck design and game play levels, the player has demonstrated a knowledge of the markets.  Of course, it is also important that you know your assets.  In building a deck, you must know what resources are available to you in order to be able to construct a competitive deck.  In game play, you must know what resources are available to you in order to allow your fellowship to survive and your shadow to kill.  For example, lets return to the Valiant Man of the West vs. Moria Swarm scenario.  Perhaps you included 4 Valiant Man of the West in your deck . . . but only 1 Aragorn&#39;s Bow.  Already, you can see that you desperately need that bow.  In order to increase your deck throughput, you could discard that Valiant Man in the hopes of reaching your Bow.  At the very least, you know that there are 3 more copies of the Valiant Man of the West that you should be able to draw into if you don&#39;t get that bow.  Thus, by sacrificing that Valiant Man of the West, you increase your probability of getting the cards that you need while at the same time not making too great of a sacrifice, because you know your assets.  Essentially, knowing the market and your assets affords you the luxury of knowing what to expect.  And when you know what to expect, you are better equipped to form the best goals from deck design to site 9 and execute so that you can achieve those goals.    <br />
<br />
BALANCE SHORT TERM AND LONG TERM<br />
<br />
In order to achieve success, you have created goals that are both clearly defined AND attainable.  Now, we are going to categorize those goals.  Some of your goals pertain to short-term success and others pertain to long-term success.  In truth, you will find that you have short-term and long-term goals throughout the Adventure Path.  But you must be careful.  Sometimes, the means for your short-term success and long-term success are at odds with each other.  Often, the mark of a veteran player is that they do not let the terms of their short-term success outweigh the terms of their long-term success (or vice-versa).  They strike a balance.  In order to achieve any measure of success in LotR, you too must strike that balance.<br />
<br />
At the most basic game-mechanic level, you can separate the Shadow and Free People sides with regards to the immediate demand and permanence of their respective goals.  Free People cards are long-term investments.  The purpose of every Free People card that you play is to increase your fellowship&#39;s ability to reach the end of the adventure path alive.  Shadow cards, however, are short-term investments.  Every Shadow card that you play has a purpose of paying dividends in wounds and doing maximum damage to the opposing fellowship, right now!  In the mechanics of deck design, there is an immediate, game imposed balance on these long-term and short-term goals--the symmetry of Free People and Shadow.  Each side must have the same number of cards.  However, the balance should go deeper than that.  If your deck intends to overwhelm, you have obviously placed an emphasis on the short-term.  Your primary goal is not to reach the end of the Adventure Path.  As such, you design your Shadow to achieve this goal, and then you fit your Free People side into the parameters and constraints set by your Shadow design.  Conversely, if your purpose is to reach the end of the Adventure Path, you will fit your Shadow to similar constraints.  But still, in either of these two examples, you have failed to identify an even better design--a deck that balances Shadow and Free People.  Yes, it is possible to build a deck that both marches to the end and overwhelms.  This is the strongest design, because it affords you the latitude to respond to your opponent&#39;s goals, and thereby increase your fortune and chances of winning.  <br />
<br />
Of course, I am not saying that you should only strike this balance in deck design.  Many game situations will arise through your playing career where you will have to make these same difficult decisions.  Do I discard that A Ranger&#39;s Versatility at Site 4?  Do I play Lurtz at site 2?  Do I make that second move?  In one form or another, each of these considerations is laden with an inherent compromise between long-term and short-term goals.  Unfortunately, I cannot give you any hard and fast rules for the correct approach to these exchanges.  They are situational.  Instead, I can only tell you to weigh the long-term against the short-term and find that right solution.  Your greatest opportunity for success comes when you balance these two goals.  Still, I will attempt to illustrate my point by exploring one of the above three situations.<br />
<br />
I think I could achieve a near unanimous consensus that Lurtz is one of the most powerful and most feared minions in the LotR universe.  The Servant of Isengard is easily capable of inflicting 5 wounds (a 1.4 rate of exchange), and then possibly more if you have the right support cards at the right time.  This level of damage can be devastating to an opposing fellowship, so it is no surprise that you will often find multiples in a deck, and quite possibly multiples stocking a player&#39;s hand.  There is a popular taboo in all card games that power cards win game and there is never a wrong time to use them.  Let me impress upon you that nothing can be further from the truth.  Perhaps, you drew Lurtz in your opening hand.  Immediately, you begin to drool at the prospect.  You start searching for the first available opportunity to unleash him on your opponent.  It becomes a short-term goal.  Well, perhaps your opponent gives you 11 twilight during his first turn.  Immediately, that opportunity presents itself.  But think!  Lurtz by himself will only inflict 3 wounds at Site 2 (a 3.0 rate of exchange).  If you use him in this capacity, Lurtz will scarcely live up to half his potential.  What if you muzzle Lurtz for a little while?  Mightn&#39;t it be wiser (and more economical) to play your Uruk Slayer and Uruk Fighter, instead?  Together, they can inflict 4 wounds (1 more than Lurtz for a 2.75 rate of exchange) and preserve Lurtz&#39;s long-term damage potential.  AND they allow you to draw more cards, further increasing your potential for victory.  By putting the reins on Lurtz, you have struck the balance between your long-term and short-term goals, and therefore maximized your potential for victory.<br />
<br />
Finally, as you think about this rule and it&#39;s application to deck building and game play, allow me to add a bit of food for thought.  Timing and Card Advantage are two hot topics of LotR deck builders and players.  They are constantly discussed in the forum of deck reviews and articles.  Well, what is timing?  What is card advantage?  Timing is nothing more than the ability to resist the urge to allow short-term goals to overcome long-term goals.  Card Advantage is nothing more than the ability to resist the urge to allow long-term goals to overcome short-term goals.  So, as you can see, striking the balance between short-term and long-term is imperative to your success in LotR.<br />
<br />
IN SUMMARY<br />
<br />
Hopefully, I have managed to convince you that there is a vast degree of economics involved in every aspect of the Lord of the Rings universe.  Furthermore, I may have caused you to view certain game dynamics and mechanics in a different light.  If I have managed to succeed in either of these two endeavors, than this article is a success.  However, I must admit that nothing I have suggested is groundbreaking or new.  Not at all!  There is a governing logic steeped in common sense that commands all of my rules.  <br />
<br />
Buy Low, Sell High!--Reduce the number of wounds that your Fellowship receives and increase the number of wounds that your Shadow delivers.  The Twilight-Wound rate of exchange is just a mathematical representation of that principle.  <br />
<br />
Clearly Defined, Attainable Goals--Look ahead and figure out how your deck is going to win.  Knowing the market and your assets is nothing more than having an awareness of cards and combination and knowing what you can do to beat them.<br />
<br />
Balance Long-Term and Short-Term goals--Know where you are going; know how you&#39;re going to get there; and don&#39;t stray from that path.  <br />
<br />
As you can see, it&#39;s all common sense.  Still, I encourage you to think of LotR within these constraints because they will help you to perform better in the long run.  And if you take nothing else from this article, I still maintain that the Twilight-Wound Rate of Exchange is an excellent measure of your deck&#39;s effectiveness.  So, keep these principles in mind, from deck design to site 9, and you will become the Alan Greenspan of the Middle Earth Exchange.  And if all else fail, just follow the law of Supply and Demand . . .  <br />
<br />
&quot;Your cards demand that you supply your opponent with a beatdown!&quot;<br />
<br />
I hope this article was informative.  Enjoy!  And I look forward to seeing you in the pits . . . <br />
<br />
Devon &quot;Middle Earth&#39;s Enron&quot; Clark<br />
